{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493278"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1273"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1273"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.07,0.08,0.05,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114821"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1273"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96825"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15054"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42272"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114821"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with worsening dyspnoea. She has a medical history of known heart failure with reduced ejection fraction secondary to ischaemic heart disease. Her last echocardiogram demonstrated a LVEF of 40%. Her current medications include perindopril 10mg daily, bisoprolol 10mg daily, atorvastatin 80mg daily, aspirin 100mg daily, dapaglifozin 10 mg daily, spironolactone 25 mg daily and tiotropium inhaled 18microg daily. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 58/min and regular, blood pressure 150/100mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and she is afebrile.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate medication to add to improve long-term heart failure control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Furosemide","Digoxin","Ivabradine","Verapamil","Sacubitril/valsartan"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman has inadequately optimised heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEf) despite the four heart failure medications. The next medication to commence which will have both morbidity and mortality benefit for her heart failure is a neprilysin inhibitor + angiotensive receptor antagonist (\u003Cstrong\u003Esacubitril/valsartan\u003C/strong\u003E); this will complete the four pillars of heart failure (beta blocker, SGLT-2 inhibitor, aldosterone antagonist, neprilysin inhibitor+ angiotensin receptor blocker).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E may improve her symptomatic shortness of breath but there is no evidence it has long-term morbidity or mortality benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E can be added as a next line option if symptoms are not optimally controlled following addition of sacubitril/valsartan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIvabradine\u003C/strong\u003E should only be used in HFrEf if heart rate is \u0026gt;70/min despite maximal beta-blocker therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium channel blockers like \u003Cstrong\u003Everapamil \u003C/strong\u003E(except amlodipine and felodipine) should generally be avoided in HFrEf since they provide no functional or mortality benefit and may worsen outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Remember the four pillars of left ventricular dysfunction treatment (betablocker, SGLT-2 inhibitor, aldosterone antagonist, neprolysin inhibitor+ angiotensin receptor blocker).","Additional medication can be added to help with LV dysfunction such as digoxin and ivabradine"],"references":["2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines","Khan ZM, Briere JB, Olewinska E, Khrouf F, Nikodem M. Ivabradine in patients with heart failure: a systematic literature review. J Mark Access Health Policy. 2023 Oct 4;11(1):2262073. doi: 10.1080/20016689.2023.2262073"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96825"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1273"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96825"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:12:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1273"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114821"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.eme